  <p class="lede first reveal">Pinterest SEO sounds like something requiring a certification and a spreadsheet. It is genuinely simpler than that. Pinterest is trying to answer a question, and it can only use the words you gave it. Most pins fail because they never gave it any.</p>

    <div class="chapter  reveal"><span class="bignum">01</span><div class="num">Chapter One</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="decides">How Pinterest decides what to show</h2></div>
    <p class="answer reveal">Pinterest reads the words in your pin title, description, board name, and profile to work out what your pin is about — then shows it to people searching those words.</p>
    <p class="reveal">It is genuinely that mechanical. There is no mystery algorithm punishing you. There is a system reading text and matching it to searches.</p>
    <p class="reveal">Which means a gorgeous pin with a headline like "Sunday Reset ✨" has told Pinterest almost nothing. It cannot be matched to anything, so it is shown to nobody.</p>
    <p class="reveal">The same image titled "Sunday reset routine for working moms" can now be matched to hundreds of real searches. Same design. Completely different outcome.</p>
    <div class="box tip reveal"><span class="tag"><span class="g">✦</span> The Edit</span><p>Pinterest cannot see your beautiful image. It reads your words. Aesthetics earn the click — words earn the impression.</p></div>

    <div class="chapter left reveal"><span class="bignum">02</span><div class="num">Chapter Two</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="places">The five places your keywords belong</h2></div>
    <p class="answer reveal">Keywords belong in your pin title, pin description, board name, board description, and profile — in natural sentences, never stuffed.</p>
    <p class="reveal"><strong>Pin title.</strong> The most important real estate you have. Use the actual phrase someone would type.</p>
    <p class="reveal"><strong>Pin description.</strong> Two or three natural sentences describing what the reader gets. Not a keyword list — a description.</p>
    <p class="reveal"><strong>Board name.</strong> "Pinterest Marketing" tells Pinterest what a board is about. "Pretty Things 💕" does not.</p>
    <p class="reveal"><strong>Board description.</strong> A short paragraph explaining who the board is for and what they will find.</p>
    <p class="reveal"><strong>Your profile.</strong> Your display name and bio tell Pinterest what your entire account is about, which affects everything you pin.</p>
    <figure class="figure reveal"><div class="img" style="background-image:url(/images/library/flatlay-pinterest-analytics.jpg);background-size:cover;background-position:center"></div><figcaption>Five places. Natural sentences. That is the entire technical requirement.</figcaption></figure>
    <div class="box mistake reveal"><span class="tag"><span class="g">!</span> Common Mistake</span><p>Keyword stuffing. "Meal prep meal planning meal prep ideas meal prep recipes" reads like spam to humans and adds nothing for Pinterest. Write one natural sentence instead.</p></div>

    <div class="chapter  reveal"><span class="bignum">03</span><div class="num">Chapter Three</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="finding">How to find keywords without a single tool</h2></div>
    <p class="answer reveal">Pinterest's own search bar is the best free keyword tool available — autocomplete shows you real searches ranked by real demand.</p>
    <p class="reveal">Start typing your topic and stop. Read every suggestion. Write them down. That is a keyword list, gathered in ninety seconds, from the source itself.</p>
    <p class="reveal">Then search your topic and look at the coloured tiles beneath the bar. Those are the modifiers people actually pair with your subject — beginners, on a budget, for small spaces, without a gym.</p>
    <p class="reveal">Then look at the top-ranking pins for your phrase and read their titles. Not to copy — to notice the pattern in the language your reader uses. She may not call it "meal prep." She may call it "what to cook this week."</p>
    <p class="deeper reveal"><span>Go deeper —</span> <a href="/learn/pinterest-marketing-guide">How to Get Your First 1,000 Pinterest Visitors →</a></p>

    <div class="chapter left reveal"><span class="bignum">04</span><div class="num">Chapter Four</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="fresh">What Pinterest means by fresh</h2></div>
    <p class="answer reveal">A fresh pin means a new image, not a new topic. You can — and should — make many fresh pins for the same article.</p>
    <p class="reveal">This single misunderstanding sabotages more Pinterest accounts than anything else. People hear "Pinterest wants fresh content" and assume they need a new article every week.</p>
    <p class="reveal">They do not. Pinterest wants a new <em>image</em>. Ten different pin designs pointing at one excellent article is ten fresh pins.</p>
    <p class="reveal">So write fewer, better articles. Then give each one many doors.</p>
    <div class="box check reveal"><span class="tag"><span class="g">✓</span> A fresh pin is</span><p>A new image or design · A new headline angle · Pointing at any page, new or old · Spaced out rather than dumped at once</p></div>

    <div class="chapter  reveal"><span class="bignum">05</span><div class="num">Chapter Five</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="reading">Reading your analytics without spiraling</h2></div>
    <p class="answer reveal">Watch two numbers: impressions tell you whether Pinterest understood your pin, and outbound clicks tell you whether people wanted it.</p>
    <p class="reveal">Low impressions means Pinterest does not know what your pin is about — that is an SEO problem. Fix the words.</p>
    <p class="reveal">High impressions but low clicks means Pinterest understood you fine, but the pin did not make anyone curious — that is a design or headline problem. Fix the promise.</p>
    <p class="reveal">That is the whole diagnostic. Two numbers, two fixes. Ignore everything else until those two are healthy.</p>
    <p class="deeper reveal"><span>Go deeper —</span> <a href="/learn/blogging-guide">How to Write Blog Posts That Still Get Read in a Year →</a></p>

    <div class="chapter reveal"><div class="num">Answered</div><div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div><h2 id="faq">Frequently asked</h2></div>
    <h3 class="reveal">Do hashtags work on Pinterest?</h3>
    <p class="reveal">Not meaningfully. Pinterest is a search engine — keywords in your title and description do the work hashtags do elsewhere.</p>
    <h3 class="reveal">How many keywords per pin?</h3>
    <p class="reveal">One primary phrase, used naturally in the title, plus two or three related phrases woven into the description. That is enough.</p>
    <h3 class="reveal">Should I use AI to write pin descriptions?</h3>
    <p class="reveal">It is useful for drafting variations quickly, provided you feed it the real search phrases from autocomplete and edit the results so they still sound like a person.</p>
    <h3 class="reveal">How long until SEO changes take effect?</h3>
    <p class="reveal">Give it several weeks. Pinterest re-evaluates pins over time, so changes are not instant — but they are durable once they take.</p>


